stablishing themselves. Varese spells out the conditions that lead to their long-term success, namely sudden market expansion that is neither exploited by local rivals nor blocked by authorities. Ultimately the inability of the state to govern economic transformations gives mafias their opportunity. In a series of matched comparisons, Varese charts the attempts of the Calabrese 'Ndrangheta to move to the north of Italy, and shows how the Sicilian mafia expanded to early twentieth-century New York, but failed around the same time to find a niche in Argentina. He explains why the Russian mafia failed to penetrate Rome but succeeded in Hungary. In a pioneering chapter on China, he examines the challenges that triads from Taiwan and Hong Kong find in branching out to the mainland. Based on ground-breaking field work and filled with dramatic stories, this book is both a compelling read and a sober assessment of the risks posed by globalization and immigration for the spread of mafias.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCrime and globalization. 0aMafiaxHistory. 0aOrganized crimexHistory. 0aTransnational crimexHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  a'Ndrangheta.  aBudapest.  aChina.  aChinese triads.  aHong Kong.  aItalian mafia.  aItalian migration.  aItalian organized crime.  aItaly.  aMafiosi.  aNew York City.  aProhibition.  aReggio Calabria.  aRome.  aRosario.  aRussian mafia.  aRussian mobsters.  aSicilian mafia.  aSicily.  aSolntsevo fraternity.  aSolntsevskaya.  aTaiwan.  acartels.  acorruption.  acriminal multinational corporations.  acriminal protection.  ademocracy.  aentrenchment.  ageneralized trust.  aglobalization.  aimmigration.  aliberalization.  amafia emergence.  amafia families.  amafia transplantation.  amafia.  a